data.value:
Uranus is the seventh planet from the sun. Although Uranus is mostly visible to the naked eye, it was long mistaken as a star because of the planet’s dimness and slow orbit. Another notable feature is the planet's dramatic tilt. In fact, the tilt is so dramatic that it orbits the sun on its side. This unusual orientation might have been because of a collision with a planet-size body, or several small bodies, soon after it was formed. This tilt gives rise to extreme seasons that last for about 20 years. For nearly a quarter of a Uranian year, the sun shines directly over each pole, leaving the other half of the planet to experience a long and dark winter.
Often referred to as an “ice giant” planet, Uranus has the coldest atmosphere of any of the planets in the solar system. The planet is composed of a mostly hydrogen-helium atmosphere and at least 80% of the planet is a fluid mix of water, methane and ammonia ice. Other unusual weather on Uranus includes diamond rain, which is thought to sink thousands of miles below the surface. Uranus has 27 known moons.
Uranus is named after the Greek sky god, Ouranos. It’s the only planet to be named after a Greek god instead of a Roman. Uranus has an orbit of 84 years, and a day cycle of 17 hours.
